data.content:
## Pattern Analysis

Your code has **three** Thread.Abort patterns that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` + `Stop()` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block with rollback | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Keeps thread alive after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` â€” the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown, so your rollback logic **silently never runs**. The `Thread.ResetAbort()` call also throws. Your `Stop()` method will crash at runtime.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking call can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);       // pass token for checkpoint checks
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException catch:
                // clean up partial work, then let the loop exit naturally.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully â€” replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after timeout, the thread is a background thread
        // and will be torn down at process exit. There is no forced kill in
        // modern .NET â€” if you need a hard kill, move work to a child process.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O) â€” a bool can't interrupt a blocked `GetNextItem()` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal; no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids catching unrelated OCEs from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | Loop condition `!token.IsCancellationRequested` exits naturally |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` | Actually waits for the thread, not just wall-clock time |
| *(none)* | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` owns a timer/callback â€” must be disposed |

## Critical: Update GetNextItem

Your `GetNextItem()` comment says "may block." If it blocks indefinitely, cancellation **will stall** because cooperative cancellation only works if the code checks the token. You must make it cancellation-aware:

```csharp
// BEFORE â€” blocks forever, ignores cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until an item is available
}

// AFTER â€” wakes up when cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken)
                                // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitOne`, or synchronous I/O instead:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
Thread.Sleep(5000);                  // âťŚ can't be interrupted
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);      // âś… returns immediately on cancel

// Replace WaitOne with cancellation-aware wait
event.WaitOne();                                          // âťŚ
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });    // âś…
```

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Cleanup logic silently lost** â€” The `ThreadAbortException` catch held your `RollbackCurrentTransaction()`. If you just delete the catch without migrating it to `OperationCanceledException`, rollbacks stop happening on cancellation.

2. **Token not passed through the call chain** â€” Every blocking or long-running method (`GetNextItem`, `ProcessItem`) must accept and forward the token. One missing link and cancellation stalls at that point.

3. **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** â€” Leaks timer and callback registrations. Always wrap in `IDisposable` or `using`.

4. **No forced kill exists** â€” If `GetNextItem` calls uncooperative third-party code that ignores the token, the thread will hang. The only escape hatch is moving that work to a **child process** and calling `Process.Kill()`.
